Supervised Learning - Foundations Project: ReCell¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The data was collected in the year 2021. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • normalized_new_price: Normalized price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • normalized_used_price: Normalized price of the used/refurbished device in euros

Observation from Dataset¶

There are 3454 rows and 15 columns in the dataset.

  1. brand_name - There are 34 unique brand_name. There are 502 other brand_name followed by 341 Samsung brand and 251 Huawei brand phone.brand_name is string datatype and has no missing values
  2. os - There are 4 unique os. Almost 93% os are Android followed by 3.97% of others.os is string datatype and has no missing values
  3. screen_size - This is float datatype.Average screen size are 13.73 cm. Minimum screen size is 5.08 cm and maximum screen size is 30.71 cm. Screen size has median of 12.83 cm. There are no missing values
  4. 4g - There are 2 unique values for 4g yes or no. Almost 67.6% phone are 4g and 32.4% phone are not 4g.4g is string datatype and has no missing values
  5. 5g - There are 2 unique values for 5g yes or no. Almost 95.6% phone are not 5g and only 4.4% phone are 5g.5g is string datatype and has no missing values
  6. main_camera_mp - This is float datatype.Average value is 9.46 megapixel. Minimum main camera mp is 0 and maximum main camera mp is 48. Main camera mp has median of 8. There are 179 missing values.
  7. selfie_camera_mp - This is float datatype.Average value is 6.55 megapixel. Minimum selfie camera mp is 0 and maximum main camera mp is 32. Selfie camera mp has median of 5. There are 2 missing values.
  8. int_memory - This is float datatype.Average internal memory is 54.6 gb. Minimum internal memory is 0.0 gb and maximum internal memory is 1024 gb. Internal memory has median of 32 gb. There are 4 missing values
  9. ram - This is float datatype.Average ram is 4.0 gb. Minimum ram is 0.0 gb and maximum ram is 12 gb. Ram has median of 4 gb. There are 4 missing values
  10. battery - This is float datatype.Average battery capacity is 3133.40 mAh. Minimum battery capacity is 500 mAh and maximum battery capacity is 9720 mAh. Battery capacity has median of 3000 mAh. There are 6 missing values.
  11. weight - This is float datatype.Average weight is 182.75 gm. Minimum weight for the phone is 69 gm and maximum weight for the phone is 855 gm. Weight for the phone has median of 160 gm. There are 7 missing values.
  12. release_year - This is float datatype.Average year for release is 2016. Minimum value for release year is 2013 and value for release year 2020. Release year has median of 2015.5 year. There are no missing values.
  13. days_used - This is float datatype.Average days used for the phone is 675 days. Minimum days used for the phone is 91 days and maximum days used for the phone is 1094 days. Days used for the phone has median of 690.5 days. There are no missing values.
  14. normalized_used_price - This is float datatype.Average value for normalized_used_price is 4.37 euros. Minimum value for normalized_used_price is 1.54 euros and maximum value for normalized_used_price is 6.62 euros. Normalized_used_price has median of 4.41 euros. There are no missing values.
  15. normalized_new_price -This is float datatype.Average value for normalized_new_price is 5.23 euros. Minimum value for normalized_new_price is 2.9 euros and maximum value for normalized_new_price is 7.85 euros.Normalized_new_price has median of 5.25 euros. There are no missing values.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of normalized used device prices look like?
  2. What percentage of the used device market is dominated by Android devices?
  3. The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a device. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?
  4. A large battery often increases a device's weight, making it feel uncomfortable in the hands. How does the weight vary for phones and tablets offering large batteries (more than 4500 mAh)?
  5. Bigger screens are desirable for entertainment purposes as they offer a better viewing experience. How many phones and tablets are available across different brands with a screen size larger than 6 inches?
  6. A lot of devices nowadays offer great selfie cameras, allowing us to capture our favorite moments with loved ones. What is the distribution of devices offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?
  7. Which attributes are highly correlated with the normalized price of a used device?

All the above questions are answered below while performing univariate and bivariate analysis.

Model Performance Check¶

In [134]:
# Function to evaluate model performance
def score(model,train,act,desc):
    """
      Inputs:
      Used to evaluate and check model performance
      model: model used to fit the data
      train : training set or testing set or X
      pred: predicted y using model
      act: actual data from dataset or y
      desc: just for printing to make sure test or train

      Outputs:
      R_squared,Adjusted R2, rmse,mae,mape

    """
    pred = model.predict(train)
    R_squared = np.round(model.rsquared, 3),
    radj_square = np.round(model.rsquared_adj, 3),
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(act, pred))
    mae =  mean_absolute_error(act, pred)
    y_true, y_pred = np.array(act), np.array(pred)
    mape =  np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

   # Printing result
    df_pred = pd.DataFrame()
    df_pred["R_squared"] = R_squared
    df_pred["radj_squared"] = radj_square
    df_pred["rmse"] = rmse
    df_pred["mae"] = mae
    df_pred["mape"] = mape

    print( "Result for the",desc,"model are:",'\n')
    display(df_pred)

Checking for Assumptions of Linear Regression¶

These assumptions are essential conditions that should be met before we draw inferences regarding the model estimates or use the model to make a prediction.

For Linear Regression, we need to check if the following assumptions hold:-

Linearity

Independence

Homoscedasticity

Normality of error terms

No strong Multicollinearity

Checking for Multicollinearity¶

General Rule of Thumb:

If VIF is 1, then there is no correlation among the k th predictor and the remaining predictor variables, and hence, the variance of βk is not inflated at all.

If VIF exceeds 5, we say there is moderate VIF, and if it is 10 or exceeding 10, it shows signs of high multi-collinearity.

The purpose of the analysis should dictate which threshold to use

In [137]:

    index=X_train.columns,

Now that we do not have multicollinearity in our data as VIF is less then 10, the p-values of the coefficients have become reliable and we can remove the non-significant predictor variables.

Now we can remove column with p values more then 0.05 but we can not drop all columns at once so we will follow following step

Build a model, check the p-values of the variables, and drop the column with the highest p-value

Create a new model without the dropped feature, check the p-values of the variables, and drop the column with the highest p-value

Repeat the above two steps till there are no columns with p-value > 0.05

In [143]:
# initial list of columns
predictors = X_train.copy()
cols = predictors.columns.tolist()

# setting an initial max p-value
max_p_value = 1

while len(cols) > 0:
    # defining the train set
    x_train_aux = predictors[cols]

    # fitting the model
    model = sm.OLS(y_train, x_train_aux).fit()

    # getting the p-values and the maximum p-value
    p_values = model.pvalues
    max_p_value = max(p_values)

    # name of the variable with maximum p-value
    feature_with_p_max = p_values.idxmax()

    if max_p_value > 0.05:
        cols.remove(feature_with_p_max)
    else:
        break

selected_features = cols
print(selected_features)

import pylab

Most of the points are on straight line except the points on tails

The Shapiro-Wilk test can also be used for checking the normality. The null and alternate hypotheses of the test are as follows:

Null hypothesis - Data is normally distributed.

Alternate hypothesis - Data is not normally distributed.

In [153]:
# Shapiro test of Normality
stats.shapiro(df_pred["Residuals"])
Out[153]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.969292163848877, pvalue=2.4978867831797727e-22)

Since p-value < 0.05, the residuals are not normal as per shapiro test.

Strictly speaking - the residuals are not normal as per the qq plot on the tail ends and shapiro test. It looks close to normal as per histogram plot. However, as an approximation, we might be willing to accept this distribution as close to being normal

TEST FOR HOMOSCEDASTICITY¶

The null and alternate hypotheses of the goldfeldquandt test are as follows:

Null hypothesis : Residuals are homoscedastic

Alternate hypothesis : Residuals have hetroscedasticity

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  1. The model is able to explain 84.2% of the variation in the data and within 15.5% of the normalized_used_price on the test data, which is good. This indicates that the model is good for prediction as well as inference purposes

  2. Normalized used price of the phone is highly dependent on normalized price of new phone so value of normalized new price go up by one units then normalized price of used phone will go up by 0.423 units. They are positively correlated by factor of 0.83.

  3. Normalized used price goes up by 0.0253 unit with increase in 1 unit of screen_size, goes up by 0.0207 unit with increase in 1 unit of main_camera_mp,goes up by 0.0141 with increase in 1 unit of selfie_camera_mp and goes up by 0.021021408232354672 with increase in 1 unit of ram. So we can say that screen_size,main_camera_mp, selfie_camera_mp and ram is important feature in deciding the price of the used phone and screen size,main_camera_mp,selfie_camera_mp and ram are in positive correalation with Normlized used price with corr factor more then 0.5

  4. Normalized used price of the phone goes up by 0.047 unit if the phone is in 4G network.Normalized_used_price is heigher for phone with 4G about 4.6 euros comapred with phone does not have 4G about 3.9 euros.Similarly it is heigher for phone with 5G network about 5.2 euros comapred with phone does not have 5G about 4.3 euros.Price of a phone with 5G network is heigher then phone with 4g network. There are only 4.4% phones are with 5G network so We still need more data to find correaltion between 5G network and used price of the phone.

  5. Almost 93% phone are Andoid based OS in our data and Normalised price of the used phone goes down by 0.07 unit if it based on Other os compared it with Android os phone. As per our data we can conclude that price of phone with Andoid os are heigher then compared with other os. Again we need more data to study effect of other os on price.

  6. Normalized used price of phone goes up with the release year means phone with newer release year has more price then older release year. So we can say that release year is also important feature in deciding the price of the used phone and release year is in positive correalation with Normlized used price with corr factor of 0.51.

  7. Normalized used price of phone is in negative correaltion with the number of days used for the phone. So if the phone is used for more days then its price will be lesser then compared with phone used for less number of days. Used price of phone is in negative correaltion with days_used with factor of -0.36.

  8. Normalized used price of phone is in positive correaltion with battery and weight of the phone with corr factor of 0.61 and 0.38 respectively. As with battery, weight of the phone increases but people still prefer phone with more battery power as they can use phone for longer time without charging.
